This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

09:44 AM Defendant Jacob C Wojcik appears by video from FC jail with attorney Breanna Halyburton appearing by video as well. Alexander Paul Seifert appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Halyburton has not went over the complaint as the case was just filed this morning. Court reads charges and penalties. Halyburton would like to be heard on bond, unable to post any amount of money, asks for high signature bond or very low cash bail. Court questions where he would live. Wojcik responds. Court questions where wife lives. Wojcik responds. State - requests bond to remain, if amended, no lower than $5000 cash bond at this point. Victim would like to make a statement, asks for him to be released on a signature bond for reasons as stated by KW. State questions no contact, state asks for $20,000 signature bond. Court amends bond to a $20,000 signature bond, no violent contact with victim Kayla Wojcik, defendant must not reside in the same residence of the victim, no consumption of alcohol and submit to law enforcement for request of test of alcohol content in his system.
